  "summary": "Following a discussion with Hakaste regarding a letter from Melina Rivale and the confirmation of a scar on a deceased man's ear, the narrator (Lime) visits Mrs. Lamech at 62 Wilbraham Crescent. Lime clarifies that he is not a detective involved in the recent phone booth murder case, but is instead investigating her husband, Michel. \n\nMrs. Lamech reveals that Michel plans to move to Moscow, a decision she does not fully support due to her moderate leftist views and her desire to raise their children as British. While she expresses uncertainty regarding whether Michel is involved in the Larkin case, she remains vague about his specific plans. She mentions her intention to find work, perhaps in secretarial duties, though Lime warns her against working at Cavenish Typewriting and Stenography due to the misfortune affecting its employees.\n\nAs Lime leaves, he encounters Mrs. McNaughton, who is carrying a heavy shopping bag. After helping her to her kitchen, Lime discovers that the bag, which she claimed contained cornflakes and watermelon, actually contains three bottles of whiskey. He concludes that this explains her unsteady gait and cheerful demeanor. Finally, while walking toward Albany Road, Lime meets Mr. Brand, who inquires about the progress of the Rivale case and the identification of the body.",
